                    </div>

                    <h4>Browser Extensions</h4>
                    <p>
                        Install browser extensions to seamlessly capture job listings while browsing. Extensions work with 
                        Chrome, Edge, and other Chromium-based browsers. Visit the <a href="/extension-install">Extensions</a> page
                        for installation instructions.
                    </p>
                     <p class="text-muted mb-0">
                         Extension source folders are located under <code>BrowserExtensions</code> in the repository.
                     </p>

                    <h4>Job Classification</h4>
                    <p>
                        Use the powerful rules engine to automatically classify jobs as they're added. Define rules based on 
                        job title, description, company, location, remote status, and more. Rules can automatically mark jobs 
                        as interested/not interested, or suitable/unsuitable based on your criteria.
                    </p>

                    <hr />

                    <h4>Running Locally</h4>
                    <p>
                        Job Tracker can run entirely on your local machine without SQL Server using <strong>LocalMode</strong>.
                        This stores all data as JSON files in the <code>Data</code> folder.
                    </p>
                    <ol>
                        <li>Clone the repository and open a terminal in the project directory</li>
                        <li>
                            Set <code>LocalMode</code> to <code>true</code> in <code>appsettings.json</code>:
                            <pre class="bg-light p-2 mt-1 rounded"><code>"LocalMode": true</code></pre>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            Run the app:
                            <pre class="bg-light p-2 mt-1 rounded"><code>dotnet run</code></pre>
                        </li>
                        <li>Open <code>@Navigation.BaseUri.TrimEnd('/')</code> in your browser</li>
                    </ol>
                    <p>
                        Background jobs (availability checks, ghosted detection, job crawling) run automatically
                        and can be managed from the <a href="/background-jobs">Background Jobs</a> page.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        You can also manage custom crawl entries via the <a href="/crawl-pages">Crawl Pages</a> page,
                        including per-page wait times, optional <code>{n}</code> substitution ranges, and list ordering.
                    </p>

                    <h4>Install as Desktop App</h4>
                    <p>
                        You can install Job Tracker as a standalone desktop app directly from your browser &mdash; no
                        app store or PWA required.
                    </p>
                    <div class="row mb-3">
                        <div class="col-md-6">
                            <strong>Microsoft Edge</strong>
                            <ol class="mb-0">
                                <li>Open Job Tracker in Edge</li>
                                <li>Click the <i class="bi bi-three-dots"></i> menu (top-right)</li>
                                <li>Select <strong>Apps</strong> &rarr; <strong>Install this site as an app</strong></li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="col-md-6">
                            <strong>Google Chrome</strong>
                            <ol class="mb-0">
                                <li>Open Job Tracker in Chrome</li>
                                <li>Click the <i class="bi bi-three-dots-vertical"></i> menu (top-right)</li>
                                <li>Select <strong>Cast, save, and share</strong> &rarr; <strong>Install page as app</strong></li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    <p class="text-muted">
                        This gives you a standalone window without browser tabs or address bar. The app still connects
                        to the server &mdash; it just runs in its own window.
                    </p>

